Overview of Computer Architecture\par
What is Computer Architecture\par
Computer architecture refers to the conceptual design and functional structure of a computer system.\par
It defines how hardware components such as the CPU, memory, input/output devices, and storage interact with each other to execute programs effectively.\par
In simple words, computer architecture explains how a computer system is organized and how it performs operations internally.\par
\par
Importance of Computer Architecture in Software Development\par
Understanding computer architecture is essential for software developers because:\par
\f1\bullet\tab Software performance depends on how hardware executes instructions\par
\bullet\tab Efficient memory and CPU usage improves application speed\par
\bullet\tab Helps in identifying performance bottlenecks\par
\bullet\tab Necessary for writing optimized, scalable, and reliable applications\par
\bullet\tab Important for backend systems, cloud services, and enterprise applications\par
In corporate environments like Wipro, developers are expected to write software that is hardware aware, not just functionally correct.\par
\par
Basic Terminology\par
\bullet\tab Hardware: Physical components of a computer system\par
\bullet\tab Software: Set of programs that run on hardware\par
\bullet\tab CPU: Executes instructions\par
\bullet\tab Memory (RAM): Temporary storage for running programs\par
\bullet\tab Storage: Permanent data storage (HDD/SSD)\par
\bullet\tab Input Devices: Keyboard, mouse\par
\bullet\tab Output Devices: Monitor, printer\par
\par
Central Processing Unit (CPU)\par
The CPU (Central Processing Unit) is the core component of a computer system responsible for executing instructions, performing calculations, and controlling system operations.\par
It acts as the brain of the computer.\par
\par
CPU Components and Their Functions\par
1. Control Unit (CU)\par
\bullet\tab Fetches instructions from memory\par
\bullet\tab Decodes instructions\par
\bullet\tab Controls data flow between CPU, memory, and I/O devices\par
2. Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU)\par
\bullet\tab Performs arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division)\par
\bullet\tab Performs logical operations (AND, OR, NOT, comparison)\par
3. Registers\par
\bullet\tab Small, high speed memory inside CPU\par
\bullet\tab Stores instructions, data, addresses, and intermediate results\par
4. Cache Memory\par
\bullet\tab Stores frequently used data and instructions\par
\bullet\tab Faster than RAM\par
\bullet\tab Reduces CPU waiting time\par
\par
How a CPU Executes Instructions\par
CPU executes instructions using the Instruction Cycle, also called the Fetch Decode Execute cycle.\par
Step 1: Fetch\par
\bullet\tab Instruction is fetched from memory\par
\bullet\tab Stored in the Instruction Register\par
\bullet\tab Program Counter points to the next instruction\par
Step 2: Decode\par
\bullet\tab Control Unit decodes the instruction\par
\bullet\tab Determines required operation and operands\par
Step 3: Execute\par
\bullet\tab ALU performs the operation\par
\bullet\tab Data is processed\par
\bullet\tab Result is generated\par
Step 4: Store (Write Back)\par
\bullet\tab Result is stored in register or memory\par
\bullet\tab Program Counter is updated\par
This cycle repeats continuously until program execution completes.\par
\par
CPU Performance Factors\par
1. Clock Speed\par
\bullet\tab Measures how many cycles CPU executes per second\par
\bullet\tab Higher clock speed \f2\u8594?\f0  faster execution\par
2. Number of Cores\par
\f1\bullet\tab Multi core CPUs execute tasks in parallel\par
\bullet\tab Improves multitasking and performance\par
3. Cache Size\par
\bullet\tab Larger cache \f2\u8594?\f0  fewer memory accesses\par
\f1\bullet\tab Faster data availability\par
4. Architecture and Instruction Set\par
\bullet\tab Efficient instruction sets improve performance\par
\bullet\tab Examples: x86, ARM\par
5. Word Length\par
\bullet\tab Amount of data CPU can process at a time\par
\bullet\tab 64 bit CPUs handle more data efficiently\par
