\par
In large web applications like Amazon, many users access the same pages repeatedly, such as the home page, offers page, product listings, etc. If every request goes directly to the database, it increases load on the database and slows down the application. To avoid this problem, cache is used.\par
Cache is a temporary memory that stores frequently accessed data so that it can be served quickly without querying the database again.\par
Why Cache is Used\par
\f1\bullet\tab Database access is slow compared to memory access\par
\bullet\tab Repeated queries for the same data waste time and resources\par
\bullet\tab High traffic can overload the database\par
\bullet\tab Cache helps in faster response and better performance\par
Therefore, cache is used to improve speed, scalability, and user experience.\par
Position of Cache in the Architecture\par
In the given diagram:\par
\bullet\tab Client sends request through the browser\par
\bullet\tab Cache is present in the UI layer (Amazon server side)\par
\bullet\tab API layer and database are accessed only when required\par
Cache acts as a middle layer between UI and API\par
\par
How Cache Works (Flow Explanation)\par
First Request (Cache Miss)\par
1.\tab User opens amazon.in in the browser\par
2.\tab UI layer checks cache\par
3.\tab Data is not present in cache (cache miss)\par
4.\tab Request is sent to API layer\par
5.\tab API fetches data from database\par
6.\tab Data is returned to UI\par
7.\tab UI stores the data in cache\par
8.\tab Page is shown to the user\par
\par
Next Requests (Cache Hit)\par
1.\tab Another user opens the same page\par
2.\tab UI layer checks cache\par
3.\tab Data is found in cache (cache hit)\par
4.\tab Data is directly returned to UI\par
5.\tab Page is shown immediately\par
\f3\u10145?\f0  No API call\par
\f3\u10145?\f0  No database access\par
\par
\par
Why Cache is Faster Than Database\par
\f1\bullet\tab Cache stores data in RAM (memory)\par
\bullet\tab Database stores data on disk\par
\bullet\tab Memory access is much faster than disk access\par
\bullet\tab Cache avoids query execution and network delay\par
Because of this, cache provides data in milliseconds, while database access takes more time.\par
\par
Advantages of Using Cache\par
\bullet\tab Faster page loading\par
\bullet\tab Reduced database load\par
\bullet\tab Better handling of high traffic\par
\bullet\tab Improved system performance\par
\bullet\tab Cost effective and scalable\par
Example\par
Amazon home page data like banners and offers does not change for every second. So this data is stored in cache and reused for many users instead of fetching again from database.\par
\par
Short Conclusion\par
Cache improves application performance by storing frequently used data in memory and serving it quickly without repeatedly accessing the database.\par
