Input / Output (I/O) Systems\par
Overview of I/O Systems\par
An Input/Output (I/O) system is responsible for enabling communication between a computer system and the external world. It allows the system to receive input, process data, and deliver output efficiently.\par
In a computer system, the CPU cannot directly interact with devices like keyboards, displays, disks, or network cards. The I/O system acts as an interface that manages this interaction in a controlled and optimized manner.\par
________________________________________\par
Purpose of I/O Systems\par
The main objectives of an I/O system are:\par
\bullet\tab To transfer data between CPU, memory, and external devices\par
\bullet\tab To hide hardware complexity from the user and application programs\par
\bullet\tab To improve system performance and CPU utilization\par
\bullet\tab To support multiple devices simultaneously\par
\par
\par
\par
Components Involved in I/O Communication\par
1.\tab CPU\par
o\tab Initiates I/O operations\par
o\tab Executes instructions related to data transfer\par
o\tab Controls the overall operation of the system\par
2.\tab Main Memory\par
o\tab Temporarily stores data being transferred\par
o\tab Acts as an intermediate buffer between CPU and I/O devices\par
3.\tab I/O Devices\par
o\tab Input devices (keyboard, mouse, scanner)\par
o\tab Output devices (monitor, printer)\par
o\tab Storage devices (SSD, HDD)\par
o\tab Network devices\par
4.\tab I/O Controllers\par
o\tab Specialized hardware that manages communication between CPU and I/O devices\par
o\tab Reduces direct CPU involvement\par
5.\tab System Bus\par
o\tab Provides data, address, and control paths between CPU, memory, and I/O devices\par
\par
Communication Between CPU, Memory, and I/O Devices\par
The communication between CPU, memory, and I/O devices follows a structured flow:\par
1.\tab The CPU issues an I/O request\par
2.\tab The request is forwarded to the I/O controller\par
3.\tab Data is transferred between the I/O device and memory\par
4.\tab The CPU is notified once the operation is complete\par
To improve efficiency, modern systems use interrupts and Direct Memory Access (DMA) so that the CPU does not remain idle waiting for I/O operations to finish.\par
\par
Modes of I/O Communication\par
1. Programmed I/O\par
\bullet\tab CPU actively waits and checks for device status\par
\bullet\tab Simple but inefficient\par
\bullet\tab Causes CPU wastage\par
2. Interrupt Driven I/O\par
\bullet\tab Device interrupts CPU when ready\par
\bullet\tab Improves CPU efficiency\par
\bullet\tab Widely used in modern systems\par
3. Direct Memory Access (DMA)\par
\bullet\tab Data transferred directly between device and memory\par
\bullet\tab CPU involvement is minimal\par
\bullet\tab Used for high speed devices such as disks and network cards\par
\par
Importance of I/O Systems in Real World Applications\par
In enterprise grade applications:\par
\bullet\tab Large volumes of data are transferred continuously\par
\bullet\tab Efficient I/O handling improves system throughput\par
\bullet\tab Poor I/O design leads to bottlenecks and performance degradation\par
Therefore, optimized I/O systems are critical for scalability, reliability, and performance, especially in corporate environments like Wipro projects.\par
\par
Summary\par
An I/O system enables communication between the CPU, memory, and external devices. It manages data transfer efficiently using controllers, interrupts, and DMA, ensuring optimal system performance and resource utilization.\par
