Understanding Computer Networking\par
What is Networking\par
Computer networking is the practice of connecting two or more computers or devices so that they can share data, resources, and services with each other.\par
A network allows systems to communicate using standard rules (protocols) over wired or wireless media. In today\rquote s corporate environment, networking is the backbone for applications, cloud services, databases, and enterprise systems.\par
\par
Why Networking is Important\par
Networking is important because it enables:\par
\bullet\tab Resource sharing (files, printers, servers)\par
\bullet\tab Communication (emails, messaging, video calls)\par
\bullet\tab Centralized data access\par
\bullet\tab Scalability and collaboration\par
\bullet\tab Internet and cloud connectivity\par
In companies like Wipro, almost every application is network dependent, whether it is internal tools or client facing systems.\par
\par
Basic Networking Concepts\par
1. Node\par
Any device connected to a network (computer, server, mobile, router).\par
2. Network\par
A group of interconnected devices that can communicate with each other.\par
3. IP Address\par
A unique address assigned to each device to identify it on a network.\par
\bullet\tab Private IP \endash  Used within an internal network\par
\bullet\tab Public IP \endash  Used to communicate over the internet\par
4. MAC Address\par
A physical, unique identifier of a network interface card (NIC).\par
5. Bandwidth\par
The maximum data transfer capacity of a network.\par
6. Latency\par
The time taken for data to travel from source to destination.\par
\par
7. Packet\par
Data is broken into small units called packets before transmission.\par
\par
8. Router and Switch\par
\bullet\tab Switch \endash  Connects devices within the same network\par
\bullet\tab Router \endash  Connects different networks (LAN to Internet)\par
\par
Network Types\par
\bullet\tab LAN (Local Area Network) \endash  Office or building network\par
\bullet\tab WAN (Wide Area Network) \endash  Internet is the best example\par
\bullet\tab MAN (Metropolitan Area Network) \endash  City level network\par
\par
Network Models\par
Network models provide a layer based structure for communication.\par
\par
1. OSI Model (7 Layers)\par
1.\tab Physical \endash  Transmission of raw bits\par
2.\tab Data Link \endash  MAC addressing and error detection\par
3.\tab Network \endash  IP addressing and routing\par
4.\tab Transport \endash  End to end communication (TCP/UDP)\par
5.\tab Session \endash  Session management\par
6.\tab Presentation \endash  Data formatting and encryption\par
7.\tab Application \endash  User interaction layer\par
The OSI model is mainly used for understanding and learning.\par
\par
2. TCP/IP Model (4 Layers)\par
1.\tab Network Interface\par
2.\tab Internet\par
3.\tab Transport\par
4.\tab Application\par
TCP/IP is the practical model used in real world networks, including enterprise and cloud systems.\par
\par
\par
Network Protocols\par
Protocols are rules that define how data is transmitted.\par
Common Protocols\par
\bullet\tab TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)\par
Reliable, connection oriented, error checked\par
\bullet\tab UDP (User Datagram Protocol)\par
Faster, connectionless, less reliable\par
\bullet\tab HTTP / HTTPS\par
Used for web communication\par
\bullet\tab FTP\par
Used for file transfer\par
\bullet\tab DNS\par
Converts domain names to IP addresses\par
\par
Importance of Networking in Software Development\par
For software developers, networking knowledge is important to:\par
\bullet\tab Design client server applications\par
\bullet\tab Understand APIs and microservices\par
\bullet\tab Work with cloud platforms\par
\bullet\tab Debug connectivity issues\par
\bullet\tab Build scalable distributed systems\par
In corporate projects, applications are rarely standalone. They operate in networked environments.\par
\par
Summary\par
Computer networking enables communication between devices using standardized protocols and layered architectures. Understanding networking concepts, models, and protocols is essential for developing, deploying, and maintaining enterprise level software systems.\par
