1. Why Probability in Machine Learning?\par
Machine Learning works with real world data, which is uncertain, noisy, and incomplete. Probability allows ML models to handle uncertainty and make data driven predictions instead of fixed rules.\par
Simple Example\par
When predicting whether an email is spam, the model does not say \ldblquote YES or NO\rdblquote  immediately. Instead, it calculates the probability that the email is spam (e.g., 92% spam).\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\f1\bullet\tab Spam classification using Naive Bayes\par
\bullet\tab Customer churn prediction (probability that a user will leave)\par
\bullet\tab Predicting rain probability in weather models\par
 \par
\par
\par
2. Mean, Median, and Mode\par
These are measures of central tendency, used to understand where data is centered.\par
Mean\par
Average of all values.\par
Example:\par
Student marks: 60, 70, 80\par
Mean = (60 + 70 + 80) / 3 = 70\par
Median\par
Middle value after sorting.\par
Example:\par
Marks: 40, 60, 100\par
Median = 60 (helps when outliers exist)\par
Mode\par
Most frequent value.\par
Example:\par
Ratings: 5, 4, 4, 3\par
Mode = 4\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\bullet\tab Calculating average salary (mean)\par
\bullet\tab Finding typical house prices ignoring outliers (median)\par
\bullet\tab Most purchased product (mode)\par
 In ML preprocessing, these are used for:\par
\bullet\tab Data understanding\par
\bullet\tab Missing value imputation\par
\par
3. Variance and Standard Deviation\par
These measure how spread out data values are.\par
Variance\par
Average of squared distances from the mean.\par
Standard Deviation\par
Square root of variance, easier to interpret.\par
Simple Example\par
Marks: 50, 50, 50\par
\f2\u8594?\f0  Low variance (consistent performance)\par
Marks: 10, 50, 90\par
\f2\u8594?\f0  High variance (inconsistent performance)\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\f1\bullet\tab Detecting abnormal transactions in fraud detection\par
\bullet\tab Feature scaling in ML (standardization)\par
\bullet\tab Measuring risk in stock prices\par
 In ML, high variance data may need normalization.\par
\par
4. Probability Basics\par
Probability measures the chance of an event occurring (0 to 1).\par
Formula\par
Probability = Favourable Outcomes / Total Outcomes\par
Example\par
Rolling a die\par
\bullet\tab Probability of getting 3 = 1/6\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\bullet\tab Clicking an ad\par
\bullet\tab User buying a product\par
\bullet\tab Predicting success/failure of an API request\par
 ML models internally calculate probabilities for each class.\par
\par
\par
5. Conditional Probability\par
Conditional probability answers:\par
\ldblquote What is the probability of A given B has already happened?\rdblquote\par
Representation\par
P(A | B)\par
Simple Example\par
\bullet\tab Probability of passing exam given attendance > 80%\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\bullet\tab Probability of disease given symptoms\par
\bullet\tab Probability of purchase given user visited the website\par
\bullet\tab Probability of spam given certain words appear in email\par
 This is the foundation of many ML classifiers.\par
\par
6. Bayes Theorem\par
Bayes theorem updates probability when new evidence appears.\par
Formula\par
P(A | B) = (P(B | A) \f0\'d7 P(A)) / P(B)\par
Simple Explanation\par
\f1\bullet\tab P(A) \f2\u8594?\f0  Prior probability (before data)\par
\f1\bullet\tab P(A | B) \f2\u8594?\f0  Updated probability (after seeing data)\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\f1\bullet\tab Email spam filtering (Naive Bayes)\par
\bullet\tab Medical diagnosis systems\par
\bullet\tab Sentiment analysis\par
 ML models keep updating predictions based on new data.\par
\par
7. Normal Distribution\par
Normal distribution is a bell shaped curve where:\par
\bullet\tab Mean = Median = Mode\par
\bullet\tab Most data lies near the mean\par
Example\par
Student height, exam marks, sensor readings often follow normal distribution.\par
Why it matters in ML\par
\bullet\tab Many algorithms assume normally distributed data\par
\bullet\tab Helps in anomaly detection\par
\bullet\tab Used in probability density estimation\par
Real World Coding Example\par
\bullet\tab Detecting abnormal CPU usage\par
\bullet\tab Identifying outliers in test scores\par
\bullet\tab Modelling noise in signals\par
