Vectors\par
\par
\ldblquote A vector is a one dimensional array used to store related data like marks or salaries.\rdblquote\par
\par
Example:\par
import numpy as np\par
marks = np.array([85, 90, 78])\par
print(marks)\par
Output\par
[85 90 78]\par
\par
Key point:\par
\bullet\tab Vectors are 1 D (ndim = 1)\par
\bullet\tab Operations apply to all elements at once\par
\par
\par
\par
Matrices\par
\ldblquote A matrix is a two dimensional structure with rows and columns, often used to represent tabular data.\rdblquote\par
Example:\par
\par
matrix = np.array([\par
[80, 70, 90],\par
[60, 75, 88],\par
[95, 85, 91]\par
])\par
print(matrix)\par
Output\par
[[80 70 90]\par
 [60 75 88]\par
 [95 85 91]]\par
\par
Key point:\par
\bullet\tab Matrix = 2 D array\par
\bullet\tab Used to store multiple records and features\par
\par
Matrix Operations\par
\par
\ldblquote NumPy supports addition, subtraction, and multiplication of matrices.\rdblquote\par
Element wise operations\par
A + B\par
A - B\par
A * B\par
Matrix multiplication\par
np.matmul(A, B)\par
\par
Key rule:\par
Columns of A must match rows of B\par
Statistics Basics\par
\ldblquote Statistics help us summarize and understand data.\rdblquote\par
Common measures:\par
data = [60, 70, 80, 90, 100]\par
print(np.mean(data))\par
print(np.median(data))\par
print(np.var(data))\par
print(np.std(data))\par
Output\par
80.0\par
80.0\par
200.0\par
14.142135623730951\par
\par
Intuition:\par
\bullet\tab Mean \f2\u8594?\f0  average\par
\f1\bullet\tab Variance \f2\u8594?\f0  spread (squared)\par
\f1\bullet\tab Std deviation \f2\u8594?\f0  spread (actual units)\par
